  = section "The Simple Directional Coverbs: <i>šoia</i>, <i>or</i>, <i>wauk</i>, <i>kra</i>" do
    %p The coverbs <i>šoia</i> “up, upwards”, <i>or</i> “down, downwards”, <i>wauk</i> “in, into”, and <i>kra</i> “out” indicate simple motion in the corresponding directions. These coverbs effectively take the place of many motive adverbs and adpositions such as “out” (not needed) or “into” (indicated by the lative case):
    %p XXX The dogs ran outside.

    %p Destinations are typically marked just by the lative case, as the coverb itself specifies the manner of motion:
    %p XXX Go into the cellar and bring up some potatoes.
    %p XXX They already went into the train station.

    %p The coverbs <i>šoia</i> and <i>or</i> can contextually also mean “[to] upstairs” or “[to] downstairs”.
    %p XXX Bring this to your father upstairs.

    %p These coverbs may also be used with non-motion verbs with a strong directional sense:
    %p XXX I shot my rifle into the air.

  = section "The Deictic Coverbs: <i>čina</i>, <i>čits</i>, <i>as</i>, <i>eita</i>, <i>ala</i>" do
    %p The coverbs <i>čina</i> “hither, to here”, <i>čits</i> “hence, from here”, <i>as</i> “along”, <i>eita</i> “towards”, and <i>ala</i> “away” are known as the deictic coverbs, since they encode information about movement either relative to the speaker or relative to an external location.
    %p <i>Čina</i> “hither” and <i>čits</i> “hence”, in their most basic sense, mark literal movement towards or away from the speaker at the time of speech.
    %p XXX
    %p XXX

    %p However, they also often indicate a first person benefactive or malefactive respectively, marking an action as either benefitting or harming the speaker.
    %p XXX
    %p XXX (stole from me?)
    %p XXX (engine broke down on me)

    %p <i>Čina</i> and <i>čits</i> can also mark second person deixis as well as second person benefactives and malefactives, but often require an explicit second person reference if not strongly implied by context, such as a second person dative pronoun.
    %p XXX
    %p XXX I brought you a gift (since "I brought myself" a gift is somewhat illogical)

    %p The coverbs <i>eita</i> “towards” and <i>ala</i> “away” work much the same way, but relative to an external (third person) focal point.
    %p XXX
    %p XXX
    %p XXX

    %p The coverb <i>as</i> “along”, in its literal sense, marks movement along, by, or past something. The reference point may be expressed in the locative, lative, or ablative cases, with the locative case being neutral relative to the speaker, and the lative and ablative cases explicitly marking motion towards or away from the speaker:
    %p XXX by me
    %P XXX along the wall towards/away from me

    %p It also is used when both the origin and destination of motion are specified and of equal relevance.
    %p XXX from X to Y

  = section "The Structural Coverb: <i>ǧuu</i>" do
    %p The coverb <i>ǧuu</i> “homeward, into a building” marks movement in the direction of a building. Though clearly related to the noun #{t "ҕвуу", "ǧwuu"} “house, home”, it can be used to refer to any structure, even ones that would never be considered a ҕвуу.
    %p The most common usage nevertheless refers to homes, either one’s own or someone else’s. In the latter case, the owner of the home may appear in the lative case.
    %p XXX going home
    %p XXX going to someone's home

    %p With other buildings, the use of <i>ǧuu</i> indicates general movement in the direction of the building, rather than explicit movement into it (cf. English “go to the store” vs “go into the store”).
    %p XXX

    %p This coverb is also used with a handful of destinations that are not buildings at all, such as as XXX “city park” (but not XXX “national park”), XXX “work”, or XXX “marketplace”.

